[A very sad discovery. While closing caves to public traffic undoubtedly helps diminish the risk of transmission it clearly does not eliminate it completely. ProMED-mail post 20130221.1552480 states that caves closed to the public still have been found to have WNS.

Photos of the northern long-eared bat (_Myotis septentrionalis_) can be seen at http://www.arkive.org/northern-long-eared-bat/myotis-septentrionalis/image-G114081.html and of little brown bats (_Myotis lucifugus_) at http://www.kollewin.com/blog/little-brown-bat_7435/.

The state of Illinois can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at http://healthmap.org/r/1nEq. An Illinois County map can be seen at http://www.digital-topo-maps.com/county-map/illinois.shtml.

The geographical distribution of WNS as of 1 Mar 2013 can be seen on the map at http://whitenosesyndrome.org/resources/map. - Mod.TG]
